Calling [`mysqli::query`][1] removes the need to call [`mysqli::use_result`][2]. Simply assign the result of the call to `query` to your `$result` variable:

    if( $result = $mysqli-&gt;query( &quot;SELECT * FROM fadi WHERE id =&#39;&quot;.$id.&quot;&#39;&quot;) ) {
        while( $row = $result-&gt;fetch_assoc() ) {
            echo $row[&#39;email&#39;];
            echo &quot;id: &quot; . $row[&quot;email&quot;]. &quot;&lt;br&gt;&quot;;
        }
    }

Note there is no `close` function on a `mysqli_result` object, only on the connection itself, which you should only close once you have completed all accesses to the database.

Note also that if `$id` is sourced from user input you should be using prepared statements instead. See the [manual][3].


  [1]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/mysqli.query.php
  [2]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/mysqli.use-result.php
  [3]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/mysqli.quickstart.prepared-statements.php

